[severity:It bothers me. A fix would be nice]
In the following code snippet an `IDE0002: Name can be simplified` is wrongly issued on `TSelf.Baz` suggesting to simply replace it with `Baz`. However, doing so would result in a `CS8926: A static virtual or abstract interface member can be accessed only on a type parameter.`

Somehow this is related to the `class` constraint, since removing it would lead to the IDE0002 no longer being issued.

The expected behavior would be to not issue the IDE0002 here in any of the two scenarios.

```cs
public interface IFoo
{
    int Bar { get; }
}

public interface IFoo<TSelf> : IFoo where TSelf : class, IFoo<TSelf>
{
    static abstract int Baz { get; }

    int IFoo.Bar => TSelf.Baz; // IDE0002: Name can be simplified
    //int IFoo.Bar => Baz; // CS8926: A static virtual or abstract interface member can be accessed only on a type parameter.
}

public interface IFooNoClass<TSelf> : IFoo where TSelf : IFooNoClass<TSelf>
{
    static abstract int Baz { get; }

    int IFoo.Bar => TSelf.Baz; // no IDE0002 issued here
}
```

